0.body: It's inspired of cookiecutter (support of cookiecutter templates #20). It's written in rust for safety and rapidity. CRS can run hooks before and after (#21) the generation. CRS use handelbars template language.
0.title: Why ?

10.body:
crs.json file containing the data used in the template. The data is written in JSON format. There is one entry for one data. The entry is written in the following format: { "email": { "type": "string", "default": "mail@example.com", "description": "Email of the author", "placeholder": "mail@example.com", "question": "What is the email of the author?", "validators": [ "^[a-zA-Z0-9.!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+@[a-zA-Z0-9](?:[a-zA-Z0-9-]{0,61}[a-zA-Z0-9])?(?:\\.[a-zA-Z0-9](?:[a-zA-Z0-9-]{0,61}[a-zA-Z0-9])?)*$" ], "error-message": "Email must be valid" }
}
10.title: crs.json

11.body: Describe the type of the data. This can be : "string" "boolean" "select" "multiselect"
11.title: type (required)

12.body: The default value of the data.
12.title: default (optional)

13.body: Description of the data used when crs ask the user.
13.title: description (optional)

14.body: Placeholder of the data used when crs ask the user.
14.title: placeholder (optional)

15.body: Question of the data used when crs ask the user. If question isn't provided, crs will autogenerate a question.
15.title: question (optional)

16.body: An array of regexp used to validate the data.
16.title: validators (optional)

17.body: Error message used when the data is invalid. (If validators is provided)
17.title: error-message (optional)

18.body: In this file, you can add hooks and metadata for the template. This file is divised in twice part: template and hooks.
18.title: CRSTemplate.json

19.body:
In this part, you can add metadata. Exemple: { "template": { "name": "rust-template", "version": "0.1.0", "description": "A template for Rust projects", "license": "MIT", "authors": ["0xMRTT <0xMRTT@tuta.io"], "maintainers": ["0xMRTT <0xMRTT@tuta.io"], "homepage": "https://github.com/0xMRTT/rust-template", "repository": "https://github.com/0xMRTT/rust-template", "documentation": "https://github.com/0xMRTT/rust-template", "keywords": ["rust", "template"] }
}
19.title: template

2.body:
You can simply run cargo install crs and you'll have a crs command in your PATH. After that, you can use crs to generate a project. cargo install crs
crs --help
2.title: From crates.io

20.body:
In this part you can add hooks which will be run before and after the generation of the template. Hooks are a dictionnary of key/value where key is the name of the hook and value is the function to run. The value is an array of the command to run like ["/bin/sh", "-c" , "cargo build"]. Exemple: { "hooks": { "post": { "cargo build": ["/bin/sh", "-c", "cargo build"] } }
}
20.title: hooks

3.body:
You can download it on release page and simply run the binary WARNING: not ready yet wget https://github.com/0xMRTT/crs/
chmod +x crs
./crs
3.title: As binary

4.body:
git clone https://github.com/0xMRTT/crs.git
cd crs
cargo b And finally run crs ./target/debug/crs
4.title: From source

5.body: After installing crs, you can run it with only one paramaeter: the URL of the template. crs https://github.com/0xMRTT/rust-template Note: rust-template is the first template made for crs by 0xMRTT .
5.title: Getting started

6.body: You can search a template using github explore . Just search for crs template and you will see a list of templates made by the community for the community.
6.title: Search a template

7.body: Currently, the marketplace is not available. It will be available soon. #22
7.title: Use the marketplace

8.body: You don't find a template you want? You can create one yourself. Just take the tutorial: Directory structure crs.json CRSTemplate.json

8.title: Create a template

9.body: A template is composed of : template directory where the template is stored crs.json file containing the data which will answered by the users. CRSTemplate.json file containing the metadata of the template. Each file in template are written in handelbars template language.
